The paper deals with a problem of efficiently identifying overlap classes of sets, which is a fundamental problem in computational geometry and combinatorics. The problem involves manipulating sets and their intersections, which suggests that it belongs to the sub-categories of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS), Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM), Computational Geometry (cs.CG), and Combinatorics (cs.CC). Additionally, the paper proposes an algorithm that has practical and implementable worst-case complexity, which suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), where practical algorithms for network analysis are often studied.
